# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: smartnic
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:smartnic/converged-network-adapter] A **converged network adapter** (**CNA**), also called a converged network interface controller (C-NIC), is a computer input/output device that combines the functionality of a host bus adapter (HBA) with a network interface controller (NIC).
[src:smartnic/converged-network-adapter] In other words, it "converges" access to, respectively, a storage area network and a general-purpose computer network.
[src:smartnic/converged-network-adapter] Some products were marketed around 2005 with the term C-NIC which combined iSCSI storage functionality with Gigabit Ethernet.
[src:smartnic/converged-network-adapter] Later products used the marketing term converged network adapter (CNA), combining Fibre Channel over Ethernet with 10 Gigabit Ethernet, for example.
[src:smartnic/converged-network-adapter] Brocade Communications Systems offers two types of CNAs, with PCI Express generation 2.0 interfaces.
[src:smartnic/converged-network-adapter] The only difference between the two models are the number of interfaces on the cards: one or two.
[src:smartnic/converged-network-adapter] The two port model will allow connection to two different switches to create a redundant configuration without having to use two PCI slots.
[src:smartnic/converged-network-adapter] In 2009 Broadcom entered the CNA market.
[src:smartnic/converged-network-adapter] Broadcom offers their CNAs under their own brand name but also sell the application-specific integrated circuits and other related components to others.
[src:smartnic/converged-network-adapter] Their intended customers are the larger builders of server systems such as Dell and HP.
[src:smartnic/converged-network-adapter] These vendors can then include the ten Gigabit CNA with their servers: as embedded interface on the motherboard (LOM or LAN on motherboard), via a mezzanine card in blade servers or as PCI extension-card.
[src:smartnic/converged-network-adapter] Emulex offers CNAs under the Emulex brand name as the OneConnect ten Gigabit series of dual port optical and copper adapters.
[src:smartnic/converged-network-adapter] They also OEM their adapters for Cisco, Dell, EMC, Fujitsu, HDS, HP, IBM and NetApp.
[src:smartnic/converged-network-adapter] QLogic offers CNAs via their QLogic 8200 & 8300 series Converged Network Adapters.
[src:smartnic/converged-network-adapter] They offer single and dual port PCI cards with copper or optical fibre interfaces.
[src:smartnic/converged-network-adapter] QLogic CNAs are available under the QLogic brandname and as OEM cards.
[src:smartnic/converged-network-adapter] The QME CNA and drivers were supported by Citrix, NetApp, EMC and IBM.
[src:smartnic/converged-network-adapter] HP claims that their BL460c G7 was the first blade server that offers FCoE via a *LOM* (LAN on motherboard) instead of using a PCI slot or mezzanine card.
[src:smartnic/converged-network-adapter] Dell uses the QLogic 8100 series in their PowerEdge servers.
[src:smartnic/converged-network-adapter] For the M-series, blade-servers for the M1000e use the custom made dual-port mezzanine card QME8142.
[src:smartnic/converged-network-adapter] For the normal tower and rack servers Dell offers an OEM version of the standard QME8152.
[src:smartnic/converged-network-adapter] Cisco Systems offered Fibre Channel over Ethernet in their Unified Computing System product line via *Virtual Interface Cards* (VICs).
[src:smartnic/converged-network-adapter] These cards make it possible to create multiple virtual HBAs or NICs within each physical VIC.
[src:smartnic/converged-network-adapter] Intel demonstrates how the term *Converged Network Adapter* is really a marketing term, as they sell the X710-DA2/DA4 adapters that don't actually support FCoE.
[src:smartnic/data-plane-development-kit] The **Data Plane Development Kit** (**DPDK**) is an open source software project managed by the Linux Foundation.
[src:smartnic/data-plane-development-kit] It provides a set of data plane libraries and network interface controller polling-mode drivers for offloading TCP packet processing from the operating system kernel to processes running in user space.
[src:smartnic/data-plane-development-kit] This offloading achieves higher computing efficiency and higher packet throughput than is possible using the interrupt-driven processing provided in the kernel.
[src:smartnic/data-plane-development-kit] DPDK provides a programming framework for x86, ARM, and PowerPC processors and enables faster development of high speed data packet networking applications.
[src:smartnic/data-plane-development-kit] It scales from mobile processors, such as Intel Atom, to server-grade processors, such as Intel Xeon.
[src:smartnic/data-plane-development-kit] It supports instruction set architectures such as Intel, IBM POWER8, EZchip, and ARM.
[src:smartnic/data-plane-development-kit] It is provided and supported under the open-source BSD license.
[src:smartnic/data-plane-development-kit] DPDK was created by Intel engineer Venky Venkatesan, who is affectionately known as "The Father of DPDK." He died in 2018 after a long battle with cancer.
[src:smartnic/data-plane-development-kit] The DPDK framework creates a set of libraries for specific hardware/software environments through the creation of an Environment Abstraction Layer (EAL).
[src:smartnic/data-plane-development-kit] The EAL hides the environment specifics and provides a standard programming interface to libraries, available hardware accelerators and other hardware and operating system (Linux, FreeBSD) elements.
[src:smartnic/data-plane-development-kit] Once the EAL is created for a specific environment, developers link to the library to create their applications.
[src:smartnic/data-plane-development-kit] For instance, EAL provides the frameworks to support Linux, FreeBSD, Intel IA-32 or 64-bit, IBM POWER9 and ARM 32- or 64-bit.
[src:smartnic/data-plane-development-kit] The EAL also provides additional services including time references, generic bus access, trace and debug functions and alarm operations.
[src:smartnic/data-plane-development-kit] Using DPDK libraries one can implement a low overhead run-to-completion, pipeline or staged, event driven, or hybrid model completely in userspace eliminating kernel and kernel to user copy.
[src:smartnic/data-plane-development-kit] Hardware assists from NIC/Regex/Accelerators, libraries enhanced to make use of Intelligence Storage Acceleration (ISA) for bulk performance and accessing devices via polling helps to eliminate the performance overhead of interrupt too.
[src:smartnic/data-plane-development-kit] Hugepages are used for large memory pool allocation, to decrease the amount of lookups and page management.
[src:smartnic/data-plane-development-kit] The DPDK also includes software examples that highlight best practices for software architecture, tips for data structure design and storage, application profiling and performance tuning utilities and tips that address common network performance deficits.
[src:smartnic/data-plane-development-kit] The DPDK includes drivers for many hardware types.
[src:smartnic/data-plane-development-kit] There have been some additional out-of-tree plugin drivers in the past, which are now considered deprecated.
[src:smartnic/data-plane-development-kit] The DPDK was originally designed to run using a bare-metal mode which is currently deprecated.
[src:smartnic/data-plane-development-kit] DPDK's EAL provides support for Linux or FreeBSD userland application.
[src:smartnic/data-plane-development-kit] EAL can be extended in order to support any processors.
[src:smartnic/data-plane-development-kit] DPDK is now an open-source project under the Linux Foundation, supported by many companies.
[src:smartnic/data-plane-development-kit] The technical activities are overseen by a Technical Board.
[src:smartnic/data-plane-development-kit] Beside Intel, which is a contributor to the DPDK, several other vendors also support the DPDK within their products and some offer additional training, support and professional services.
[src:smartnic/data-plane-development-kit] The list of vendors who have announced DPDK support includes: 6WIND, ALTEN Calsoft Labs, Advantech, Brocade, Big Switch Networks, Mellanox Technologies, Radisys, Tieto, Wind River, Lanner Inc. and NXP.
[src:smartnic/data-plane-development-kit] This is 'line rate' on a 10 Gbps interface.
[src:smartnic/data-plane-development-kit] Open vSwitch (OVS) has a limited set of features running userland that can be leveraged to bypass the Linux kernel OVS processing.
[src:smartnic/data-plane-development-kit] This use case of OVS with DPDK userland is usually named OVS-DPDK.
[src:smartnic/data-plane-development-kit] It is mostly deployed with OpenStack Neutron but it assumes that many features and software-defined networking (SDN) capabilities of Openstack are disabled.
[src:smartnic/data-plane-development-kit] For instance, when OVS-DPDK is used, Neutron provides a lower level of security than when OVS kernel is used (no stateful firewalling, less security group).
[src:smartnic/data-plane-development-kit] The FD.IO VPP platform is an extensible framework that provides out-of-the-box production quality switch/router functionality.
[src:smartnic/data-plane-development-kit] It is the open source version of Cisco's Vector Packet Processing (VPP) technology: a high performance, packet-processing stack that can run on commodity CPUs, and can leverage the Poll Mode Drivers for both NICs and cryptographic acceleration hardware and libraries.
[src:smartnic/data-plane-development-kit] TRex is an open source traffic generator using DPDK.
[src:smartnic/data-plane-development-kit] It generates L4–7 traffic based on pre-processing and smart replay of real traffic templates.
[src:smartnic/data-plane-development-kit] TRex amplifies both client and server side traffic and can scale to 200 Gbit/s with one UCS using Intel XL710.
[src:smartnic/data-plane-development-kit] TRex also supports multiple streams, ability to change any packet field and provides per stream statistics, latency and jitter.
[src:smartnic/data-plane-development-kit] DTS (DPDK Test Suite) is a Python-based framework for functional tests and benchmarks.
[src:smartnic/data-plane-development-kit] It is an open-source project, started in 2014, and is hosted on dpdk.org.
[src:smartnic/data-plane-development-kit] It supports both software traffic generators like Scapy and dpdk-pktgen, and a hardware traffic generator like Ixia.
[src:smartnic/data-plane-development-kit] DDP (Dynamic Device Personalization) is one of the new advanced features implemented with DPDK.
[src:smartnic/data-plane-development-kit] It allows you to load firmware for a device dynamically, without resetting the host.
[src:smartnic/network-processor] A **network processor** is an integrated circuit which has a feature set specifically targeted at the networking application domain.
[src:smartnic/network-processor] Network processors are typically software programmable devices and would have generic characteristics similar to general purpose central processing units that are commonly used in many different types of equipment and products.
[src:smartnic/network-processor] The processing of these packets has resulted in the creation of integrated circuits (IC) that are optimised to deal with this form of packet data.
[src:smartnic/network-processor] Network processors have specific features or architectures that are provided to enhance and optimise packet processing within these networks.
[src:smartnic/network-processor] Network processors have evolved into ICs with specific functions.
[src:smartnic/network-processor] This evolution has resulted in more complex and more flexible ICs being created.
[src:smartnic/network-processor] The newer circuits are programmable and thus allow a single hardware IC design to undertake a number of different functions, where the appropriate software is installed.
[src:smartnic/network-processor] Reconfigurable Match-Tables were introduced in 2013 to allow switches to operate at high speeds while maintaining flexibility with respect to which network protocols are enabled on the device and/or how those protocols are processed.
[src:smartnic/network-processor] The company Barefoot Networks was based around these processors and was later purchased by Intel in 2019.
[src:smartnic/network-processor] An RMT pipeline relies on three main stages; the programmable parser, the Match-Action tables and the programmable deparser.
[src:smartnic/network-processor] The parser reads the packet in chunks and processes these chunks to find out which protocols are used in the packet (Ethernet, VLAN, IPv4...) and extracts certain fields from the packet into the Packet Header Vector (PHV).
[src:smartnic/network-processor] Certain fields in the PHV may be reserved for special uses such as present headers or total packet length.
[src:smartnic/network-processor] The protocols are typically programmable, and so are the fields to extract.
[src:smartnic/network-processor] The Match-Action tables are a series of units that read an input PHV and match certain fields in it using a crossbar and CAM memory.
[src:smartnic/network-processor] The result is a wide instruction that operates on one or more fields of the PHV and data to support this instruction.
[src:smartnic/network-processor] The output PHV is then sent to the next MA stage or to the deparser.
[src:smartnic/network-processor] The deparser takes in the PHV as well as the original packet and its metadata (to fill in missing bits that weren't extracted into the PHV) and then outputs the modified packet as chunks.
[src:smartnic/network-processor] The deparser, like the parser, is typically programmable and the two may share some configuration files.
[src:smartnic/network-processor] FlexNIC attempts to apply this model to Network Interface Controllers allowing servers to send and receive packets at high speeds while maintaining protocol flexibility and without increasing the CPU overhead.
[src:smartnic/network-processor] Modern network processors are also equipped with low-latency high-throughput on-chip interconnection networks optimized for the exchange of small messages among cores (few data words).
[src:smartnic/network-processor] Such networks can be used as an alternative facility for the efficient inter-core communication aside of the standard use of shared memory.
[src:smartnic/network-processor] Using the generic function of the network processor, a software program implements an application that the network processor executes, resulting in the piece of physical equipment performing a task or providing a service.
[src:smartnic/output-virtualization] In virtualization, **single root input/output virtualization** (**SR-IOV**) is a specification that allows the isolation of PCI Express resources for manageability and performance reasons.
[src:smartnic/output-virtualization] A single physical PCI Express bus can be shared in a virtual environment using the SR-IOV specification.
[src:smartnic/output-virtualization] The SR-IOV offers different virtual functions to different virtual components (e.g. network adapter) on a physical server machine.
[src:smartnic/output-virtualization] SR-IOV uses physical and virtual functions to control or configure PCIe devices.
[src:smartnic/output-virtualization] Physical functions have the ability to move data in and out of the device while virtual functions are lightweight PCIe functions that support data flowing but also have a restricted set of configuration resources.
[src:smartnic/output-virtualization] The virtual or physical functions available to the hypervisor or guest operating system depend on the PCIe device.
[src:smartnic/output-virtualization] The SR-IOV allows different virtual machines (VMs) in a virtual environment to share a single PCI Express hardware interface.
[src:smartnic/output-virtualization] In contrast, MR-IOV allows I/O PCI Express to share resources among different VMs on different physical machines.
[src:smartnic/output-virtualization] A major field of application for SR-IOV is within high-performance computing (HPC).
[src:smartnic/output-virtualization] The use of high-performance InfiniBand networking cards is growing within the HPC sector, and there is early research into the use of SR-IOV to allow for the use of InfiniBand within virtual machines such as Xen.
[src:smartnic/smartnic] A **data processing unit** (**DPU**) is a programmable computer processor that tightly integrates a general-purpose CPU with network interface hardware.
[src:smartnic/smartnic] They are also occasionally called "**IPUs**" (infrastructure processing unit) or "**SmartNICs**".
[src:smartnic/smartnic] These devices can be attractive to cloud computing providers whose servers might otherwise spend a significant amount of CPU time on these tasks, cutting into the cycles they can provide to guests.
[src:smartnic/smartnic] They see use in other kinds of data center environments as well due to their improved power consumption efficiency for routine networking tasks compared to general-purpose CPUs.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] SDN was commonly associated with the OpenFlow protocol for remote communication with network plane elements to determine the path of network packets across network switches since OpenFlow's emergence in 2011.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] However, since 2012, proprietary systems have also used the term.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] These include Cisco Systems' Open Network Environment and Nicira's network virtualization platform.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] SD-WAN applies similar technology to a wide area network (WAN).
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] In addition to WAN use cases, SDN is also increasingly applied in telecom backbones, where it is paired with operational inventory and automation platforms to provide real-time visibility, service assurance, and simplified provisioning across multi-vendor networks.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] The history of SDN principles can be traced back to the separation of the control and data planes first used in public switched telephone networks.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] This provided a manner of simplifying provisioning and management years before the architecture was used in data networks.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) began considering various ways to decouple the control and data forwarding functions in a proposed interface standard published in 2004 named Forwarding and Control Element Separation (ForCES).
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] The ForCES Working Group also proposed a companion SoftRouter architecture.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] Additional early standards from the IETF that pursued separating control from data planes include the Linux Netlink as an IP services protocol, and a path computation element (PCE)-based architecture.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] These early attempts failed to gain traction.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] One reason is that many in the Internet community viewed separating control from data to be risky, especially given the potential for failure in the control plane.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] Another reason is that vendors were concerned that creating standard application programming interfaces (APIs) between the control and data planes would result in increased competition.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] In 2006 a young startup was founded around SDN style network topology and submitted a collection of SDN patents in 2007.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] The use of open-source software in these separated architectures traces its roots to the Ethane project at Stanford's computer science department.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] Ethane's simple switch design led to the creation of OpenFlow, and an API for OpenFlow was first created in 2008.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] In that same year, NOX, an operating system for networks, was created.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] SDN research included emulators such as vSDNEmul, EstiNet, and Mininet.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] Work on OpenFlow continued at Stanford, including with the creation of testbeds to evaluate the use of the protocol in a single campus network, as well as across the WAN as a backbone for connecting multiple campuses.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] In academic settings, there were several research and production networks based on OpenFlow switches from NEC and Hewlett-Packard, as well as those based on Quanta Computer white-boxes starting in about 2009.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] Beyond academia, the first deployments were by Nicira in 2010 to control OVS from Onix, codeveloped with NTT and Google.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] A notable deployment was Google's B4 in 2012.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] Later, Google announced the first OpenFlow/Onix deployments in is datacenters.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] Another large deployment exists at China Mobile.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] The Open Networking Foundation was founded in 2011 to promote SDN and OpenFlow.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] At the 2014 Interop and Tech Field Day, software-defined networking was demonstrated by Avaya using shortest-path bridging (IEEE 802.1aq) and OpenStack as an automated campus, extending automation from the data center to the end device and removing manual provisioning from service delivery.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] SDN architectures decouple network control (control plane) and forwarding (data plane) functions, enabling the network control to become directly programmable and the underlying infrastructure to be abstracted from applications and network services.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] The OpenFlow protocol is one of the protocols used in SDN technologies.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] The explosion of mobile devices and content, server virtualization, and the advent of cloud services are among the trends driving the networking industry to re-examine traditional network architectures.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] Many conventional networks are hierarchical, built with tiers of Ethernet switches arranged in a tree structure.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] This design made sense when client-server computing was dominant, but such a static architecture may be ill-suited to the dynamic computing and storage needs of today's enterprise data centers, campuses, and carrier environments.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] Within the enterprise data center, traffic patterns have changed significantly.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] At the same time, users are changing network traffic patterns as they push for access to corporate content and applications from any type of device, connecting from anywhere, at any time.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] model, which may include a private cloud, public cloud, or some mix of both, resulting in additional traffic across the wide-area network.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] Users are increasingly employing mobile personal devices such as smartphones, tablets, and notebooks to access the corporate network.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] IT is under pressure to accommodate these personal devices in a fine-grained manner while protecting corporate data and intellectual property and meeting compliance mandates.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] Enterprises have enthusiastically embraced both public and private cloud services, resulting in unprecedented growth of these services.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] Many enterprise businesses want the agility to access applications, infrastructure and other IT resources on demand and discretely.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] IT planning for cloud services must be performed in an environment of increased security, compliance and auditing requirements, along with business reorganizations, consolidations and mergers that can rapidly change assumptions.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] Providing self-service provisioning, whether in a private or public cloud, requires elastic scaling of computing, storage and network resources, ideally from a common viewpoint and with a common suite of tools.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] requires massive parallel processing on thousands of servers, all of which need direct connections to each other.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] is fueling a constant demand for additional network capacity in the data center.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] Operators of hyperscale data center networks face the daunting task of scaling the network to previously unimaginable size, maintaining any-to-any connectivity within a limited budget.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] emerged, the need for larger data centers has increased the energy consumption of those facilities.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] applying existing routing techniques to dynamically adjust the network data plane to save energy.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] Also techniques to improve control plane energy efficiency are being researched.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] In addition, they may consume an abstracted view of the network for their internal decision-making purposes.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] An SDN Application consists of SDN application logic and one or more NBI drivers.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] SDN applications may themselves expose another layer of abstracted network control, thus offering one or more higher-level NBIs through respective NBI agents.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] The SDN controller is a logically centralized entity in charge of (i) translating the requirements from the SDN application layer down to the SDN datapaths and (ii) providing the SDN applications with an abstract view of the network (which may include statistics and events).
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] An SDN controller consists of one or more NBI agents, the SDN control logic, and the control to data-plane interface (CDPI) driver.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] The SDN datapath is a logical network device that exposes visibility and uncontested control over its advertised forwarding and data processing capabilities.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] The logical representation may encompass all or a subset of the capabilities.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] An SDN datapath consists of a CDPI agent and a set of one or more traffic forwarding engines and zero or more traffic processing functions.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] These engines and functions may include simple forwarding between the datapath's external interfaces or internal traffic processing or termination functions.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] One or more SDN datapaths may be contained in a single (physical) network element—an integrated physical combination of communications resources, managed as a unit.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] An SDN datapath may also be defined across multiple physical network elements.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] The SDN CDPI is the interface defined between an SDN controller and an SDN datapath, which provides at least programmatic control of all forwarding operations, capabilities advertisement, statistics reporting, and event notification.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] One value of SDN lies in the expectation that the CDPI is implemented in an open, vendor-neutral and interoperable way.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] SDN NBIs are interfaces between SDN applications and SDN controllers and typically provide abstract network views and enable direct expression of network behavior and requirements.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] This may occur at any level of abstraction and across different sets of functionality.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] The implementation of the SDN control plane can follow a centralized, hierarchical, or decentralized design.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] Initial SDN control plane proposals focused on a centralized solution, where a single control entity had a global view of the network.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] While this simplifies the implementation of the control logic, it has scalability limitations as the size and dynamics of the network increase.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] To overcome these limitations, hierarchical and distributed approaches have been proposed.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] In hierarchical solutions, controllers operate on a partitioned network view, while decisions that require network-wide knowledge are taken by a logically centralized root controller.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] In distributed approaches, controllers operate on their local view or they may exchange synchronization messages to enhance their knowledge.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] Distributed solutions are more suitable for supporting adaptive SDN applications.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] A key issue when designing a distributed SDN control plane is to decide on the number and placement of control entities.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] An important parameter to consider while doing so is the propagation delay between the controllers and the network devices, especially in the context of large networks.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] Other objectives that have been considered involve control path reliability, fault tolerance, and application requirements.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] In SDN, the data plane is responsible for processing data-carrying packets using a set of rules specified by the control plane.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] The data plane may be implemented in physical hardware switches or in software, such as Open vSwitch.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] The memory capacity of hardware switches may limit the number of rules that can be stored whereas software implementations may have higher capacity.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] Flow table entries may be populated in a proactive, reactive, or hybrid fashion.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] In the proactive mode, the controller populates flow table entries for all possible traffic matches for this switch in advance.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] This mode can be compared with typical routing table entries today, where all static entries are installed ahead of time.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] Following this, no request is sent to the controller since all incoming flows will find a matching entry.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] A major advantage in proactive mode is that all packets are forwarded at line rate (considering all flow table entries in TCAM) and no delay is added.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] In the reactive mode, entries are populated on demand.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] If a packet arrives without a corresponding match rule in the flow table, the SDN agent sends a request to the controller for further instruction.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] The controller examines the SDN agent requests and provides instructions, installing a rule in the flow table for the corresponding packet if necessary.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] The hybrid mode uses the low-latency proactive forwarding mode for a portion of traffic while relying on the flexibility of reactive mode processing for the remaining traffic.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] Software-defined mobile networking (SDMN) is an approach to the design of mobile networks where all protocol-specific features are implemented in software, maximizing the use of generic and commodity hardware and software in both the core network and radio access network.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] It is proposed as an extension of SDN paradigm to incorporate mobile network specific functionalities.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] Since 3GPP Rel.14, a Control User Plane Separation was introduced in the Mobile Core Network architectures with the PFCP protocol.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] An SD-WAN is a WAN managed using the principles of software-defined networking.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] The main driver of SD-WAN is to lower WAN costs using more affordable and commercially available leased lines, as an alternative or partial replacement of more expensive MPLS lines.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] Control and management are administered separately from the hardware, with central controllers allowing for easier configuration and administration.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] An SD-LAN is a Local area network (LAN) built around the principles of software-defined networking, though there are key differences in topology, network security, application visibility and control, management and quality of service.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] SD-LAN decouples control, management and data planes to enable a policy-driven architecture for wired and wireless LANs.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] SD-LANs are characterized by their use of a cloud management system and wireless connectivity without the presence of a physical controller.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] SDN architecture may enable, facilitate or enhance network-related security applications due to the controller's central view of the network, and its capacity to modify behavior or the data plane at any time.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] The security implications of SDN architecture remain under study.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] Several research works on SDN have already investigated security applications built upon the SDN controller, with different aims in mind.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] Distributed denial of service (DDoS) detection and mitigation, as well as botnet and worm propagation, are some concrete use cases of such applications.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] Proposed applications periodically collect network statistics from the forwarding plane of the network in a standardized manner (e.g., using OpenFlow), and then apply classification algorithms on those statistics in order to detect any network anomalies.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] If an anomaly is detected, the application instructs the controller how to reprogram the data plane in order to mitigate it.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] Another kind of security application leverages the SDN controller by implementing some moving target defense (MTD) algorithms.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] MTD algorithms are typically used to make any attack on a given system or network more difficult than usual by periodically hiding or changing key properties of that system or network.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] In traditional networks, implementing MTD algorithms is not a trivial task since it is difficult to build a central authority able to determine, for each part of the system to be protected, which key properties are hidden or changed.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] In an SDN network, such tasks become more straightforward thanks to the centrality of the controller.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] One application can, for example, periodically assign virtual IPs to hosts within the network, and the mapping of virtual IP to real IP is then performed by the controller.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] Another application can simulate some fake opened/closed/filtered ports on random hosts in the network in order to add significant noise during scanning performed by an attacker.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] Additional value regarding security in SDN-enabled networks can also be gained using FlowVisor and FlowChecker.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] The former tries to use a single hardware forwarding plane sharing multiple separated logical networks.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] Following this approach, the same hardware resources can be used for production and development purposes as well as separating monitoring, configuration and Internet traffic, where each scenario can have its own logical topology, which is called a slice.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] In conjunction with this approach, FlowChecker realizes the validation of new OpenFlow rules that are deployed by users using their own slice.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] SDN controller applications are mostly deployed in large-scale scenarios, which requires comprehensive checks of possible programming errors.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] A system to do this called NICE was described in 2012.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] Introducing an overarching security architecture requires a comprehensive and protracted approach to SDN.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] Since it was introduced, designers are looking at possible ways to secure SDN that do not compromise scalability.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] One architecture called SN-SECA (SDN+NFV) Security Architecture.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] Distributed applications that run across datacenters usually replicate data for the purpose of synchronization, fault resiliency, load balancing and getting data closer to users (which reduces latency to users and increases their perceived throughput).
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] Also, many applications, such as Hadoop, replicate data within a datacenter across multiple racks to increase fault tolerance and make data recovery easier.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] All of these operations require data delivery from one machine or datacenter to multiple machines or datacenters.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] The process of reliably delivering data from one machine to multiple machines is referred to as Reliable Group Data Delivery (RGDD).
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] SDN switches can be used for RGDD via installation of rules that allow forwarding to multiple outgoing ports.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] For example, OpenFlow provides support for Group Tables since version 1.1 which makes this possible.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] Using SDN, a central controller can carefully and intelligently setup forwarding trees for RGDD.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] Such trees can be built while paying attention to network congestion/load status to improve performance.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] For example, MCTCP is a scheme for delivery to many nodes inside datacenters that relies on regular and structured topologies of datacenter networks while DCCast and QuickCast are approaches for fast and efficient data and content replication across datacenters over private WANs.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] Network Function Virtualization, or NFV for short, is a concept that complements SDN.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] Thus, NFV is not dependent on SDN or SDN concepts.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] NFV separates software from hardware to enable flexible network deployment and dynamic operation.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] NFV deployments typically use commodity servers to run network services software versions that previously were hardware-based.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] These software-based services that run in an NFV environment are called Virtual Network Functions (VNF).
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] SDN-NFV hybrid program was provided for high efficiency, elastic and scalable capabilities NFV aimed at accelerating service innovation and provisioning using standard IT virtualization technologies.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] SDN provides the agility of controlling the generic forwarding devices such as the routers and switches by using SDN controllers.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] On the other hand, NFV agility is provided for the network applications by using virtualized servers.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] It is entirely possible to implement a virtualized network function (VNF) as a standalone entity using existing networking and orchestration paradigms.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] However, there are inherent benefits in leveraging SDN concepts to implement and manage an NFV infrastructure, particularly when looking at the management and orchestration of VNFs, and that's why multivendor platforms are being defined that incorporate SDN and NFV in concerted ecosystems.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] Deep packet inspection (DPI) provides network with application-awareness, while SDN provides applications with network-awareness.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] Although SDN will radically change the generic network architectures, it should cope with working with traditional network architectures to offer high interoperability.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] When using an SDN based model for transmitting multimedia traffic, an important aspect to take account is the QoE estimation.
[src:smartnic/software-defined-networking] To estimate the QoE, first we have to be able to classify the traffic and then, it's recommended that the system can solve critical problems on its own by analyzing the traffic.
